Hi Mathieu,

Sorry, not addressed your previous comments here.

For the trace id, each coresight component has 7 bits to store the trace 
id. So the trace id should be from 1 to 127 as 0 is invalid.

Apart from TPDMs/STM/ETMs, we also have other coresight components in 
our internal device. About 80 ids are already used.

Some components have fixed trace id in HW. If we use functions below to 
count the trace id, there will be conflict to other components.

Can we use 1-15 for etm trace idsÂ  and 16 - 127 for other coresight 
components ? And handle trace ids in its' own driver ?


static inline int coresight_get_system_trace_id(int id)
{
 Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  /* Start system IDs above the highest per CPU trace ID. */
 Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  return coresigth_get_trace_id(cpumask_last(cpu_possible_mask) + 1);
}

static inline int coresight_get_trace_id(int cpu)
{
 Â Â  Â /*
 Â Â  Â  * A trace ID of value 0 is invalid, so let's start at some
 Â Â  Â  * random value that fits in 7 bits and go from there.Â  Since
 Â Â  Â  * the common convention is to have data trace IDs be I(N) + 1,
 Â Â  Â  * set instruction trace IDs as a function of the CPU number.
 Â Â  Â  */
 Â Â  Â return (CORESIGHT_ETM_PMU_SEED + (cpu * 2));
}

Thanks

Jinlong Mao

